          "body": "The second law addresses interpersonal financial fraud — what Leviticus 6:1-7 calls the 'sins of mankind' (5:6). The legal content is similar to Leviticus 6, but Numbers 5 adds a crucial theological reframe: the sin against a neighbor is simultaneously 'acting unfaithfully against the LORD' (*maal ba-Adonai*, 5:6). This is not hyperbole; it is the Torah's consistent claim that human relationships are conducted under divine covenantal supervision. To defraud your neighbor is to betray the LORD's own covenant order. The prescribed remedy moves through three steps: confession (*yadah*, 5:7), full restitution plus twenty percent, and a ram of atonement (5:8). The combination is significant — the horizontal wrong (full restitution to the injured party) and the vertical wrong (atonement before God) are both required, and neither cancels the other. The extension in 5:8-10 handles the case where the wronged party has died with no heir: the restitution reverts to the LORD, administered through the priest. The theological logic is elegant — moral debts do not dissolve when the human creditor dies; they revert to God, who never dies and never forgets."
