        "excerpt": "You shall send them outside the camp so that they will not defile their camp where I dwell in their midst.",
        "body": "The chapter opens not with an explanation of what defilement is — Leviticus 11-15 has already supplied that — but with a command derived from a theological fact: the LORD dwells in the camp, therefore the camp must be clean. The logical structure is deductive, moving from theological premise (divine habitation) to practical command (send the unclean out). The three categories named — the leprous, the person with a discharge, and the corpse-contaminated — represent the spectrum of ritual impurity addressed in the Levitical purity system. Their expulsion is temporary, not permanent; restoration procedures are provided. But while the condition persists, the integrity of the holy space must be maintained.\n\nThe command is addressed to the corporate community ('command the sons of Israel,' 5:2), not merely to individuals or priests. This is a matter of communal responsibility for communal holiness. The compliance report of verse 4 underscores this: the whole community acted in obedience. Israel's covenant life is not merely individual piety; it is the shared maintenance of a holy space around a holy God. The brief note 'just as the LORD had spoken to Moses, thus the sons of Israel did' is Numbers' standard obedience formula (cf. 1:54; 2:34; 3:51), and its presence signals that this compliance is itself presented as praiseworthy covenant faithfulness.\n\nThe Hebrews 13:11-13 connection is not allegorizing away the text's plain sense — it is following the typological logic that the author of Hebrews himself supplies. Jesus suffered 'outside the gate' in order to bear the defilement that made Israel's insiders unclean. The boundary between inside and outside the camp, which in Numbers marked the boundary between holiness and defilement, in the New Testament becomes the locus of atonement: the clean One goes outside so that the unclean may come in.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shakhan* (to dwell, v. 3) is the root of *mishkan* (tabernacle/dwelling-place) — God's 'dwelling' in the camp is not incidental presence but the very category the tabernacle is built to facilitate. *Tavekh* (in the midst of them, v. 3) is the spatial preposition of intimacy — not distant lordship but indwelling nearness. The holiness demand flows precisely from that nearness."
